    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "Tamarac officially incorporated July 19 1963, founded by developer Kenneth E. Behring.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1,
        2
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1",
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.tamarac.gov/History"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The city was named Tamarac after the nearby Tamarac Country Club in Oakland Park.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        10
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tamarac%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "In 1963, Behring built Tamarac Lakes Section One and Two east of State Road 7, the city’s first development.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        13
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tamarac%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Behring later added Tamarac Lakes North, Tamarac Lakes Boulevard, Tamarac Lakes South, the Mainlands of Tamarac Lakes, and the Woodlands community.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        14,
        15
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tamarac%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "In the late 1970s, Tamarac de‑annexed a long line of commercial buildings from State Road 7 to Northwest 31 Avenue, keeping the city a bedroom community.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        16
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tamarac%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "Tamarac enjoys a tropical monsoon climate (Köppen Am), similar to much of the Caribbean.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        23
